Updated User Requirements Checklist
App Name: Personal Cyber Safety Coach
(Built for the ISACA Orange County Sponsored Problem Challenge)
This checklist is written in plain, everyday language so anyone (students, families, parents, part-time workers, small clubs) can understand exactly what the app should feel like and do.
It now includes both quick Share Sheet sharing and easy in-app pasting/uploading — because great user experience means people can use whichever way feels most natural to them.
1. Core Features – What the App MUST Do (MVP)
I can quickly share any link or screenshot/photo of a suspicious message straight from email, SMS, WhatsApp, Instagram, or anywhere else using my phone’s normal “Share” button (Share Sheet).
I can also open the app and paste or type things directly — just like chatting with any helpful AI:
Paste a full email or message text
Paste or type a link/URL
Attach or upload a photo/screenshot of the message
The app has a simple, friendly chat-style input bar at the bottom where I can type, paste, or add my link/email/image in one place — super easy and natural to use.
The app instantly tells me in simple words: SafeSuspiciousHigh Risk
The app gives me the top 3 reasons why it made that decision, written like a friendly coach (short bullet points, no jargon).
The app shows a clear checklist of what to do next (for example: “Don’t click”, “Check with the real company”, “Turn on 2-step verification”, “Report it”).
The app teaches me a quick 30-second micro-lesson so I learn something useful for next time.
The app works in English and Spanish (and I can easily switch languages).
2. Privacy & Safety – Must-Haves (Non-Functional)
The app is privacy-first – it never saves my links, messages, or personal data on any server.
If I accidentally share or paste a message that contains my name, email, phone number, or other private info, the app automatically hides (redacts) those details before analyzing it.
No personal data ever leaves my phone unless I choose to create and send a report myself.
The app has a strong safety guardrail: if I try to paste a phishing link and then ask “help me make an even better phishing message,” the app politely refuses and explains why it won’t help with anything harmful.
3. High-Impact & Easy-to-Use Experience
The app feels warm, encouraging, and easy — like talking to a helpful friend, not a robot.
Anyone (even grandparents or kids) can use it without reading any instructions.
I can choose whichever input method feels best — Share Sheet for speed or the in-app chat bar for when I want to type/paste directly — making the whole experience smooth and flexible.
The whole process is super fast — I get my answer in just a few seconds.
The app helps me feel safer and more confident every time I use it (real-world impact: fewer scams, less stress, less money lost).
4. Bonus / Stretch Features (Extra Nice-to-Have)
If the link is High Risk, the app can create a simple PDF report with all the details, risk reasons, and recommendations. I can save it or forward it to my school IT, boss, family, or friends to educate them.
The explanations include trustworthy reference links (just like ChatGPT shows sources) so I can see where the advice comes from and trust it more.
The app can give a confidence score (“I’m 85% sure this is risky — here’s an easy way to double-check safely”).
Multi-language support for more languages beyond English and Spanish (stretch goal).
5. Overall Success Goals (How We Know the App Is Great)
A non-expert (student, parent, small club) would actually open and use this app in real life.
The explanations are so clear that anyone can understand them and feel confident.
The app protects my privacy and never helps bad actors.
The app is simple enough that a university, club, or small business could easily share it with their people.


